Problem Statement

Business Context

Renewable energy sources play an increasingly important role in the global energy mix, as the effort to reduce the environmental impact of energy production increases.

Out of all the renewable energy alternatives, wind energy is one of the most developed technologies worldwide. The U.S Department of Energy has put together a guide to achieving operational efficiency using predictive maintenance practices.

Predictive maintenance uses sensor information and analysis methods to measure and predict degradation and future component capability. The idea behind predictive maintenance is that failure patterns are predictable and if component failure can be predicted accurately and the component is replaced before it fails, the costs of operation and maintenance will be much lower.

The sensors fitted across different machines involved in the process of energy generation collect data related to various environmental factors (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) and additional features related to various parts of the wind turbine (gearbox, tower, blades, break, etc.).

Objective

ReneWind is a company working on improving the machinery/processes involved in the production of wind energy using machine learning and has collected data of generator failure of wind turbines using sensors. They have shared a ciphered version of the data, as the data collected through sensors is confidential (the type of data collected varies with companies). Data has 40 predictors, 20000 observations in the training set and 5000 in the test set.

The objective is to build various classification models, tune them, and find the best one that will help identify failures so that the generators could be repaired before failing/breaking to reduce the overall maintenance cost. The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model. These will result in repairing costs.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures where there is no detection by the model. These will result in replacement costs.
  • False positives (FP) are detections where there is no failure. These will result in inspection costs.

It is given that the cost of repairing a generator is much less than the cost of replacing it, and the cost of inspection is less than the cost of repair.

1 in the target variables should be considered as failure and 0 represents No failure.

Data Description

The data provided is a transformed version of the original data which was collected using sensors.

  • Train.csv - To be used for training and tuning of models.
  • Test.csv - To be used only for testing the performance of the final best model.

Both the datasets consist of 40 predictor variables and 1 target variable.

Executive Summary

We build a cost-sensitive classifier to predict wind-turbine generator failures (1 = failure, 0 = no failure) from 40 anonymized sensor-derived predictors.

The notebook enforces no data leakage via scikitlearn Pipelines and selects a decision threshold to minimize expected business cost (FN TP FP TN=0).

We report standard metrics (ROCAUC, PRAUC, Recall, Precision, F1/F2) and pick a final model from seven neural network variants (baseline + six improvements: depth, optimizer, dropout, class weights).

These are the techniques and knowledge considered for the project:

  • SGD and Adam are standard optimizers for deep neural nets

  • unequal misclassification costs require costsensitive thresholds.

  • PRAUC is more informative than ROCAUC under class imbalance.

  • caution that modern nets can be miscalibrated and benefit from posthoc scaling.

Bivariate Analysis

Why we used Spearman, MI, and class-wise density plots instead of scatterplots

Because the dataset has 40 anonymized continuous features, most of the predictive signal is not in simple 2-D plots but in higher-dimensional combinations of features. A scatterplot of any two variables would mostly show overlap between failure and non-failure cases.

To uncover relationships that might still matter:

  • We used Spearman correlation to capture monotonic (up or down) relationships with the target.

  • We used mutual information to detect nonlinear associations that correlation can miss.

  • We then used class-wise density plots to visualize how the distributions of the most informative features differ between failures and non-failures.

This combination provides clearer evidence of which features carry predictive signal without overwhelming us with uninterpretable scatter clouds.

X_train, X_valid, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(

# Numeric pipeline (median impute + scale)

    ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="median")),
    ("scaler", StandardScaler())
])

preprocess = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[("num", numeric_transformer, num_cols)],
    remainder="drop"
)

preprocess.fit(X_train)
X_train_proc = preprocess.transform(X_train)
X_valid_proc   = preprocess.transform(X_valid)

# Class weights from training prevalence
classes = np.array([0,1])
class_weights_arr = compute_class_weight(
    class_weight="balanced", classes=classes, y=y_train
)
CLASS_WEIGHT = {int(c): w for c, w in zip(classes, class_weights_arr)}

Model Building

In[12]:
# ---- Business costs (set per business; keep FP < TP < FN) ----
C_TN = 0.0
C_FP = 1.0     # inspection (lowest)
C_TP = 5.0     # repair (middle)
C_FN = 20.0    # replacement (highest)

def expected_cost_from_counts(tp, fn, fp, tn):
    return tp*C_TP + fn*C_FN + fp*C_FP + tn*C_TN

def confusion_counts_at_threshold(y_true, y_prob, t=0.5):
    y_pred = (y_prob >= t).astype(int)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=[0,1]).ravel()
    return tp, fn, fp, tn

def eval_at_threshold(y_true, y_prob, t):
    tp, fn, fp, tn = confusion_counts_at_threshold(y_true, y_prob, t)
    prec = precision_score(y_true, (y_prob>=t).astype(int), zero_division=0)
    rec  = recall_score(y_true, (y_prob>=t).astype(int), zero_division=0)
    f1   = f1_score(y_true, (y_prob>=t).astype(int), zero_division=0)
    beta = 2.0
    if prec+rec == 0:
        fbeta = 0.0
    else:
        fbeta = (1+beta**2) * (prec*rec) / (beta**2*prec + rec + 1e-12)
    cost = expected_cost_from_counts(tp, fn, fp, tn)
    return {
        "threshold": t, "precision": prec, "recall": rec, "f1": f1, "f2": fbeta,
        "tp": tp, "fn": fn, "fp": fp, "tn": tn, "expected_cost": cost
    }

def search_cost_optimal_threshold(y_true, y_prob, tie_break="recall_then_prauc", n_grid=200):
    # grid on unique probabilities + linspace for stability
    uniq = np.unique(y_prob)
    grid = np.unique(np.concatenate([np.linspace(0,1,n_grid), uniq]))
    best = None
    for t in grid:
        r = eval_at_threshold(y_true, y_prob, t)
        if best is None or r["expected_cost"] < best["expected_cost"] - 1e-9:
            best = r
        elif abs(r["expected_cost"] - best["expected_cost"]) <= 1e-9:
            # tie-breaker: higher recall, then higher precision
            if r["recall"] > best["recall"] + 1e-12 or (
                abs(r["recall"] - best["recall"]) <= 1e-12 and r["precision"] > best["precision"] + 1e-12
            ):
                best = r
    return best

def summarize_probs(y_true, y_prob):
    return {
        "roc_auc": roc_auc_score(y_true, y_prob),
        "pr_auc":  average_precision_score(y_true, y_prob)
    }

Model Evaluation Criterion

Write down the model evaluation criterion with rationale

Metric Choice and Rationale

In settings where false negatives are much more expensive than repairs or inspections, the decision rule should shift the threshold to reduce FN.

Costsensitive thresholding is standard. Because the positive class is likely minority, PRAUC is emphasized alongside ROCAUC. Class weights and calibration are appropriate under imbalance and probability miscalibration.

In[13]:
# Check for GPU and set policy
try:
    physical_devices = tf.config.list_physical_devices('GPU')
    if len(physical_devices) > 0:
        tf.config.set_visible_devices(physical_devices[0], 'GPU')
        tf.config.experimental.set_memory_growth(physical_devices[0], True)
        print("GPU found and configured:", physical_devices[0])
    else:
        print("No GPU found. Using CPU.")
except:
    print("Error configuring GPU. Using CPU.")


def build_model(input_dim: int,
                hidden_layers=(32,),
                dropout=None,
                optimizer="sgd",
                lr=1e-2,
                momentum=0.9,
                l2=0.0):
    # Use GPU if available
    with tf.device('/GPU:0' if tf.config.list_physical_devices('GPU') else '/CPU:0'):
        model = keras.Sequential(name="nn_clf")
        model.add(layers.Input(shape=(input_dim,)))
        for units in hidden_layers:
            model.add(layers.Dense(units, activation="relu",
                                   kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(l2) if l2>0 else None))
            if dropout:
                model.add(layers.Dropout(dropout))
        model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))

        if optimizer.lower() == "adam":
            opt = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr)
        elif optimizer.lower() == "rmsprop":
            opt = optimizers.RMSprop(learning_rate=lr)
        else:
            opt = optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=lr, momentum=momentum, nesterov=True)

        model.compile(
            optimizer=opt,
            loss="binary_crossentropy",
            metrics=[
                keras.metrics.AUC(name="roc_auc", curve="ROC"),
                keras.metrics.AUC(name="pr_auc",  curve="PR"),
                keras.metrics.Precision(name="precision"),
                keras.metrics.Recall(name="recall"),
            ],
        )
    return model

def train_and_evaluate(model_name, model_kwargs, use_class_weights=False, verbose=0):
    input_dim = X_train_proc.shape[1]
    model = build_model(input_dim=input_dim, **model_kwargs)

    es   = callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor="val_pr_auc", mode="max", patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)
    rlrp = callbacks.ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor="val_pr_auc", mode="max", patience=5, factor=0.5, min_lr=1e-5)

    fit_kwargs = dict(
        x=X_train_proc, y=y_train, epochs=200, batch_size=256,
        validation_data=(X_valid_proc, y_valid),
        callbacks=[es, rlrp], verbose=verbose,
    )
    if use_class_weights:
        fit_kwargs["class_weight"] = CLASS_WEIGHT

    hist = model.fit(**fit_kwargs)
    y_valid_prob = model.predict(X_valid_proc, verbose=0).ravel()

    curves = summarize_probs(y_valid, y_valid_prob)  # ROC & PR AUC from sklearn
    opt    = search_cost_optimal_threshold(y_valid, y_valid_prob)

    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_valid, (y_valid_prob>=opt["threshold"]).astype(int), labels=[0,1]).ravel()
    return model, {
        "model_name": model_name,
        "params": {**model_kwargs, "use_class_weights": use_class_weights},
        "history": {k: [float(x) for x in v] for k, v in hist.history.items()},
        "valid_probs": y_valid_prob.tolist(),
        "roc_auc": float(curves["roc_auc"]),
        "pr_auc":  float(curves["pr_auc"]),
        "opt_threshold": float(opt["threshold"]),
        "recall_at_t": float(opt["recall"]),
        "precision_at_t": float(opt["precision"]),
        "f2_at_t": float(opt["f2"]),
        "expected_cost_at_t": float(opt["expected_cost"]),
        "confusion_at_t": {"tn": int(tn), "fp": int(fp), "fn": int(fn), "tp": int(tp)},
        "keras_params_count": int(model.count_params()),
    }

def summarize_probs(y_true, y_prob):
    return {
        "roc_auc": roc_auc_score(y_true, y_prob),
        "pr_auc":  average_precision_score(y_true, y_prob)
    }

def add_model(name, kw, use_cw=False, verbose=0):
    m, r = train_and_evaluate(name, kw, use_class_weights=use_cw, verbose=verbose)
    trained[name] = m
    all_results.append(r)
    display(pd.DataFrame([{
        "Model": r["model_name"],
        "Val ROC-AUC": r["roc_auc"],
        "Val PR-AUC": r["pr_auc"],
        "t*": r["opt_threshold"],
        "Recall@t*": r["recall_at_t"],
        "Precision@t*": r["precision_at_t"],
        "F2@t*": r["f2_at_t"],
        "Expected Cost@t*": r["expected_cost_at_t"],
        "Params": r["keras_params_count"],
    }]))

    # Confusion matrix with percentages
    y_true = y_valid
    y_pred = (np.array(r["valid_probs"]) >= r["opt_threshold"]).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=[0,1])
    cm_sum = cm.sum()
    cm_perc = cm / cm_sum * 100

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,4))
    im = ax.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap="Blues")

    classes = ["No Failure (0)", "Failure (1)"]
    ax.set(
        xticks=np.arange(cm.shape[1]),
        yticks=np.arange(cm.shape[0]),
        xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes,
        ylabel="True label",
        xlabel="Predicted label",
        title=f"Confusion Matrix with %  {name}"
    )
    plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")

    # Annotate counts and percentages
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i in range(cm.shape[0]):
        for j in range(cm.shape[1]):
            ax.text(j, i,
                    f"{cm[i, j]}\n({cm_perc[i, j]:.1f}%)",
                    ha="center", va="center",
                    color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

In[23]:
# ---- helpers (simple) ----
def expected_cost(tp, fn, fp, tn):
    return tp*C_TP + fn*C_FN + fp*C_FP + tn*C_TN

def eval_at_t(y_true, y_prob, t):
    y_pred = (y_prob >= t).astype(int)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=[0,1]).ravel()
    prec = tp/(tp+fp+1e-12); rec = tp/(tp+fn+1e-12)
    beta = 2.0
    f2 = (1+beta**2)*prec*rec/(beta**2*prec + rec + 1e-12) if (prec+rec)>0 else 0.0
    return dict(t=t, tp=tp, fn=fn, fp=fp, tn=tn,
                precision=prec, recall=rec, f2=f2,
                expected_cost=expected_cost(tp, fn, fp, tn))

def print_test_report(y_true, y_prob, t, tag="Final Test Report"):
    e = eval_at_t(y_true, y_prob, t)
    roc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_prob)
    ap  = average_precision_score(y_true, y_prob)
    print(f"\n=== {tag} ===")
    print(f"ROC-AUC: {roc:.3f} | PR-AUC: {ap:.3f}")
    print(f"Threshold t*: {e['t']:.6f}")
    print(f"Confusion (TN, FP, FN, TP): ({e['tn']}, {e['fp']}, {e['fn']}, {e['tp']})")
    print(f"Precision@t*: {e['precision']:.3f} | Recall@t*: {e['recall']:.3f} | F2@t*: {e['f2']:.3f}")
    print(f"Expected Cost@t*: {e['expected_cost']:,.0f}")
    return e, roc, ap

thresholds = np.linspace(0,1,101)
costs = []
y_valid_prob = final_model_fresh.predict(X_valid_proc, verbose=0).ravel()
for t in thresholds:
    preds = (y_valid_prob >= t).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_valid, preds)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    cost = fn*C_FN + tp*C_TP + fp*C_FP
    costs.append((t,cost))
t_opt, cost_opt = min(costs, key=lambda x: x[1])
print(f"Optimal threshold={t_opt:.2f}, Expected cost={cost_opt}")

Takeaway

  • Our validation process selected Model 6 as cost-optimal at 1463. On the test set, cost rose to 1943, mostly due to extra false negatives. This highlights the instability of thresholds under class imbalance and high FN costs.
  • In production, we would (1) prefer cross-validation cost averages, (2) monitor drift in live data, (3) re-tune thresholds periodically, and (4) look to improve accuracy by providing more signals through additional labels
  • Aside from the test vs validation differences, model 6 is the best choice lowest cost with balanced metrics
  • In model 6 final training results, ROC/PR curves on test are still strong (ROC-AUC 0.93, PR-AUC 0.89)
  • shallow or very deep models underperform
  • best direction is moderate depth plus dropout with Adam, which resulted in the model being not too complex and cost optimal

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

Write down some insights and business recommendations based on your observations.

Operating point

  • best model is model 6 (deep + dropout 0.2 Adam)
  • cost optimal threshold is ~0.09
  • recall is more important since missed failures cost the most
  • this setting catches about 9 out of 10 failures while keeping inspection volume under control

Expected operations

  • for every 10k turbines monitored the model prevents hundreds of replacements and triggers a similar number of inspections, cutting overall costs a few percent.

Process

  • alerts above threshold should flow into an inspection queue
  • highest risk predictions (top 10%) get priority and should be checked within 24h
  • review false positives weekly to refine inspection steps and reduce wasted site visits

Data improvements

  • features are anonymized and pre-scaled, but more signal can be created
  • keep failure labels updated often so the model doesnt drift
  • revisit threshold choice each month since costs and failure rates can shift
